[thinking] **Testing PasswordEncoder Behavior**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I’m thinking about how to test the PasswordEncoder bean and its effect on default user password handling. If a custom PasswordEncoder is present, I need to ensure that it doesn't default to prefixing with {noop}. Current tests cover the default behavior, but there’s a possibility for a scenario that’s not addressed. Should I create a new PasswordEncoder bean and define a nested @Configuration? It’s essential to confirm that a custom encoder can handle pre-encoded passwords properly while being mindful of deprecated features.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Examining Password Handling**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I’m considering whether the builder for the password accepts no ID. It seems that UserDetails can handle a password without needing an ID. I think I could assert that the context has just one PasswordEncoder bean and that the UserDetails password equals the rawConfigured one. This also brings up dynamic access, though I’m unsure if I should introduce a new inner class. I may want to test how SecurityFilterAutoConfiguration behaves when a custom DelegatingFilterProxyRegistrationBean exists. There's a lot to inspect!
[thinking] 
